SIMPLE: warden
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Warden
<hw>Ward"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wardein</ets>, OF. <ets>wardein</ets>, <ets>gardein</ets>,
<ets>gardain</ets>, F. <ets>gardien</ets>. See <er>Guardian</er>, and
<er>Ward</er> guard.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A keeper; a guardian; a watchman.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He called to the <qex>warden</qex> on the . . . battlements.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir. W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An officer who keeps or guards; a keeper; <as>as,
the <ex>warden</ex> of a prison</as>.</def> <-- chief officer of a
prison. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A head official; <as>as, the <ex>warden</ex> of a
college</as>; specifically <fld>(Eccl.)</fld>, a churchwarden.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[Properly, a keeping pear.]</ety> <def>A large, hard
pear, chiefly used for baking and roasting.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would have had him roasted like a <qex>warden</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Warden pie</b></col>, <cd>a pie made of warden
pears.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wardenship</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Wardenry</ent>⟦br⟧
